  <content>
    <title>Continuous Discovery Habits</title>

    <summary>Weekly customer discovery framework where the Product Trio (PM, Design, Tech) maintains an Opportunity Solution Tree. Every roadmap item traces to verbatim customer evidence. Agents automate mechanical work: triage, transcript coding, tree synthesis.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Sporadic discovery produces roadmaps that reflect the loudest internal voice, not customer evidence. Teams at Spotify, CarMax, and Tesco consistently out-discover competitors by maintaining one customer interview per week as a keystone habit. The OST forces every roadmap item to have a traceable chain: outcome ← opportunity ← verbatim quote with participant ID.</p>
      <p>Without a structured system, feedback is dominated by the loudest voices, scattered across channels, and never linked to backlog items. Users feel unheard; PMs lack signal on what to build next. A centralized pipeline with a fixed taxonomy and mandatory close-loop step converts feedback from noise into a ranked priority input that feeds directly into roadmap sessions.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>PM owns one product area and needs a defensible weekly cadence (one interview/week minimum).</item>
        <item>Roadmaps drifting to feature-list mode — leadership cannot articulate what outcome each item serves.</item>
        <item>Product Trio is forming and needs a shared artifact to triangulate on.</item>
        <item>Quarterly planning prep — agents synthesize 60–80 interviews into a refreshed OST that becomes input to roadmap, OKRs, and discovery sprints.</item>
        <item>"Why are we building this?" challenges from leadership — OST + interview log answer with a traceable chain (outcome ← opportunity ← evidence quotes).</item>
        <item>Solo PM at a startup wants an LLM to triage support tickets, NPS verbatims, sales-call recordings into the OST as candidate opportunities for trio review.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-PMF zero-to-one with founder-led customer development — Torres' framework assumes you have a product, an outcome metric, and access to customers. Use customer-development and jobs-to-be-done instead.</item>
        <item>Regulated domains where weekly outside-customer interviews require legal review per touchpoint (clinical trials, fintech KYC research) — cadence breaks under the gating overhead.</item>
        <item>B2B with fewer than 20 logo accounts and a 12-month sales cycle — weekly interviews aren't sustainable; switch to monthly executive briefings + quarterly synthesis.</item>
        <item>Mature growth-stage where experimentation-at-scale has displaced qualitative discovery; here CDH is a complement (it generates hypotheses), not the primary loop.</item>
        <item>One-shot launches and migrations (rebrand, platform cutover) — they need stakeholder management and program management, not weekly touchpoints.</item>
        <item>Agencies/consultants on fixed-scope contracts — without ownership of the outcome, the OST has no anchor.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="framework-overview">
      <p>The Opportunity Solution Tree (OST) is the central artifact. Teresa Torres' framework maintains one OST per outcome metric, allowing the Product Trio to share a single view of customer needs, solutions, and assumption tests. Every week, the PM adds new customer evidence, the trio reviews opportunities for "next solution to test," and the team runs targeted assumption tests before solutions enter the roadmap.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every roadmap item MUST link to one OST opportunity. That opportunity MUST have verbatim quotes with participant ID + interview date from at least one past-behavior interview. Opportunities phrased as "build X" or "add X" are rejected; they belong as candidate solutions under a real opportunity.</statement>
        <rationale>Solution-shaped opportunities collapse the distinction between need and proposed answer. Without this separation, the team builds features without validating the underlying problem exists or is worth solving.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The PM MUST conduct at least one customer interview per week, minimum. Interview subjects MUST be sampled across segment, recency, and plan-tier to avoid over-sampling the same power-users. Sampling diversity checks MUST happen pre-interview; agents must enforce diversity (segment, recency, churn-status, plan-tier) before each round.</statement>
        <rationale>Weekly interviews as a keystone habit create organizational memory and prevent feature-list drift. Diverse sampling prevents over-indexing on vocal minorities and surfaces unmet needs in undersampled segments.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>One outcome per OST per quarter. If two outcomes are in scope, build two trees and contend with the cross-tree dependency explicitly — do not merge.</statement>
        <rationale>Merged outcomes create metric ambiguity and make assumption testing untestable. Separate trees let teams focus on falsifiable, time-bounded outcomes without strategic hedging.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Quote-level provenance is non-negotiable: every opportunity links to >=1 quote_id with participant + date. The interview transcript is source of truth; never let synthesis agents reason from summaries (lossy). Feed full transcripts with quote-level IDs.</statement>
        <rationale>Paraphrased evidence is lossy and drifts the OST toward solution-shaped "opportunities." Verbatim quotes with participant IDs let the trio re-listen, re-interpret, and link to other evidence months later.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Park ruthlessly — opportunities with no new evidence in 60 days get parked; archive at 180 days. Tree health beats tree completeness.</statement>
        <rationale>Unmaintained opportunities become technical debt. Parking forces the trio to regularly ask "is this still a real customer need?" and prevents the OST from becoming a dumping ground.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Lock the trio to ONE meeting per week and ship the trio-prep doc 24h before. Without prep, the meeting becomes a status update.</statement>
        <rationale>A prepared trio meeting is focused, decision-driven, and respects time. Prep shifts the meeting from "what should we talk about?" to "here are three opportunities ready for the next solution test."</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pair every opportunity with one assumption test type per dimension (desirability, viability, feasibility, usability, ethical). Cheap to enumerate, expensive to skip and learn later.</statement>
        <rationale>Assumption tests make the solution-to-opportunity link testable before investing engineering. Pre-registered tests prevent the team from shipping unvalidated solutions and convert roadmaps from "opinions in priority order" to "falsifiable hypotheses."</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a calibration interview round monthly: PM listens-only to a CS or sales call, codes it, and compares to interview-coder output. If divergence > 25%, retune the coder prompt.</statement>
        <rationale>Interview-coder agents will paraphrase quotes and conflate preferences with past-behavior evidence. Monthly calibration catches drift early and keeps the agent prompt aligned to the team's coding standards.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Anonymize PII at coding time, not at synthesis time. Once it's in the corpus, it's leaked. Discovery-delivery percentage is a contract with engineering, not a PM aspiration. If 15% gets eaten weekly, escalate or shrink scope; do not silently absorb it.</statement>
        <rationale>PII scrubbing requires a local gating step before agent coding to prevent accidental exposure to remote LLMs. Discovery-delivery commitment is meaningless without enforcement; silently absorbing discovery work trains teams to skip the practice.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>PM operates the loop; agents handle the mechanical parts. Five hand-offs per week, each gated by PM review. OST lives at `.aidocs/product_docs/discovery/ost.yaml`. Interview transcripts at `discovery/interviews/YYYY-MM-DD-participant-hash.md`. All agents read/write through this folder; no in-app SaaS state without an export step.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents and their roles:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Feedback-triage (haiku): Daily at 8am. Input: Support tickets, NPS verbatims, sales-call notes. Output: Top-N opportunity-candidates (JSON) ranked by frequency × outcome-relevance. Route high-signal items to PM's review queue; low-signal items to a separate "consider later" archive.</statement>
        <rationale>Cheap models for collection and triage. Haiku can categorize at high volume with minimal latency, surfacing patterns that humans would miss.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Interview-prep (sonnet): Pre-interview. Input: Current OST, opportunity gap, last 4 transcripts. Output: Research questions, screener, anti-leading-question rewrites. Force questions about specific recent instances ("tell me about the last time you..."), never future predictions.</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured authoring. Interview prep keeps the PM grounded in past-behavior anchoring and prevents the interview from drifting into aspirational "would you use" territory.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Interview-coder (sonnet): Post-interview. Input: Transcript (text or audio→text). Output: Coded quotes, snapshot of "story", behavioral evidence flags. Force verbatim copy of the source span and a separate paraphrase field; downstream agents must consume verbatim only. Label every quote as past_behavior | preference | speculation; synthesizer must filter to past_behavior only for opportunity creation.</statement>
        <rationale>Interview-coder will paraphrase quotes, breaking provenance. Forcing verbatim + paraphrase lets downstream agents stay grounded in evidence. Behavior labels prevent the OST from drifting into preference-only opportunities.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>OST-synthesizer (opus): Weekly. Input: All coded quotes since last run, current OST. Output: Proposed tree-diff (add/move/dedup nodes), evidence linkage. Force a JSON-patch (RFC 6902) or YAML-diff format; reject full-tree outputs. Require N>=5 quotes from >=3 participants before emitting a theme; never manufacture cross-cutting themes from N=2 unrelated quotes.</statement>
        <rationale>Opus for synthesis where cross-corpus reasoning happens. Forcing diffs prevents drift and keeps PMs in control. Requiring N>=5 prevents hallucination of patterns from thin evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Assumption-tester (sonnet): On opportunity-promotion. Input: Solution + key assumptions. Output: List of assumption-test designs (Type-1: desirability/viability/feasibility/usability/ethical).</statement>
        <rationale>Structured enumeration of assumptions prevents teams from shipping unvalidated solutions. Sonnet is strong at structured task decomposition.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Trio-prep (sonnet): Pre-trio meeting. Input: OST, recent quotes, capacity allocation. Output: 1-page agenda; 3 opportunities ready for "next solution to test". Constrain output to specific recommendations + tradeoffs; reject hedging boilerplate like "depends on team capacity".</statement>
        <rationale>Sonnet for structured writing. Prep constraints keep the meeting focused and decision-driven.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Weekly-readout (sonnet): Friday. Input: All week artifacts. Output: weekly-discovery.md + roadmap-input.md. Roadmap-input is a delta artifact, never a rewrite. Quarterly mapper emits "promote / demote / hold / drop" recommendations versus current Now/Next/Later.</statement>
        <rationale>Weekly readouts build organizational memory. Delta artifacts keep PMs in control of major roadmap shifts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Roadmap-mapper (opus): Quarterly. Input: Full OST, outcome history, capacity. Output: Now/Next/Later updates as deltas to existing roadmap. Force it to use rolling-90d evidence count, not raw recency, to prevent bias toward last week's interviews.</statement>
        <rationale>Opus for synthesis. Quarterly mapping locks in roadmap direction driven by evidence, not opinion.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Archive-pruner (sonnet): Monthly. Input: OST nodes with no edits in 90d. Output: Archive proposals; PM approves. Set OST token budget: cap ost-synthesizer at 120k tokens per run (full OST + 1 week of transcripts). If over, archive first; never expand context.</statement>
        <rationale>Monthly pruning keeps the tree navigable. Token budgets prevent runaway costs on synthesis.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ost-schema-and-templates">
      <p>The OST schema is YAML, tree-as-code. Agents emit YAML patches; PM reviews, applies via the ost-apply script. Friday weekly readout is Markdown, ≤2 pages.</p>

      <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
outcome:
  id: outcome_2026Q2_activation
  metric: pct_new_signups_completing_first_value_action
  baseline: 0.31
  target: 0.45
  owner: pm@team.com

opportunities:
  - id: opp_login_friction
    statement: "I get locked out at SSO and give up before completing setup"
    evidence:
      - quote_id: q_2026-04-12_p042
      - quote_id: q_2026-04-19_p081
    parent: outcome_2026Q2_activation
    last_evidence_date: 2026-04-19
    status: active   # active | parked | shipped | invalidated
    solutions:
      - id: sol_passwordless_link
        assumption_tests:
          - type: desirability
            method: prototype_test
            owner: ux
          - type: feasibility
            method: spike
            owner: tech_lead
        decision: not_started   # not_started | testing | win | kill
]]></code>

      <p>Friday weekly readout skeleton (Markdown, ≤2 pages):</p>

      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
# Discovery Week of 2026-04-22

## Outcome
activation: 0.31 → 0.34 (+0.03 vs baseline)

## Touchpoints
- Interviews this week: 1 (P-091, mid-market, 13mo tenure)
- Diversity vs last 4: segment OK; tenure-skew (all >12mo) -> next sample <6mo

## OST changes (diff)
+ opportunity opp_sso_lockout (3 quotes)
~ opportunity opp_login_friction renamed → opp_setup_dropoff (broader)
- opportunity opp_dark_mode parked (no evidence in 60d)

## Assumption tests run / planned
- sol_passwordless_link prototype: desirability test scheduled Tue
- sol_self_serve_sso spike: tech_lead estimate due Fri

## Roadmap input
- Now: ship sol_setup_progress_indicator (validated, low-effort)
- Next: pilot sol_passwordless_link (assumption test pending)
- Later: re-evaluate sol_self_serve_sso pending feasibility spike

## Open questions for trio
1. Is opp_setup_dropoff a single opportunity or two (auth vs onboarding)?
2. Should we drop opp_dark_mode permanently or revisit Q3?
]]></code>

      <p>OST diff applier (scripts/ost_apply.py, ~30 lines). Agents emit diffs, PM reviews, this script applies:</p>

      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import sys, yaml, copy
from pathlib import Path

def apply_diff(ost: dict, diff: dict) -> dict:
    out = copy.deepcopy(ost)
    by_id = {o["id"]: o for o in out["opportunities"]}
    for op in diff.get("add", []):
        if op["id"] in by_id:
            raise SystemExit(f"add: id exists {op['id']}")
        out["opportunities"].append(op)
    for op in diff.get("update", []):
        if op["id"] not in by_id:
            raise SystemExit(f"update: missing {op['id']}")
        by_id[op["id"]].update(op)
    for op_id in diff.get("park", []):
        by_id[op_id]["status"] = "parked"
    for op_id in diff.get("archive", []):
        out["opportunities"] = [o for o in out["opportunities"] if o["id"] != op_id]
    return out

if __name__ == "__main__":
    ost = yaml.safe_load(Path(sys.argv[1]).read_text())
    diff = yaml.safe_load(Path(sys.argv[2]).read_text())
    Path(sys.argv[1]).write_text(yaml.safe_dump(apply_diff(ost, diff), sort_keys=False))
]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-failure-modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Weekly interview" degrades to "weekly chat with the loudest customer" — PMs over-sample the same 5 power users.</description>
        <reason>Agents must enforce sampling diversity (segment, recency, churn-status, plan-tier) before each round. Without this, the OST reflects power-user preferences, not market-wide patterns.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>OST grows monotonically; without pruning, it becomes a dumping ground. By month 6 most trees have 200+ nodes and become unusable.</description>
        <reason>Need a quarterly archive-or-promote ritual. Monthly pruning keeps the tree navigable and forces teams to drop invalidated hypotheses.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Opportunities get conflated with solutions ("opportunity: build dashboard"). Must reject solution-shaped opportunities; they belong as branches under a real opportunity.</description>
        <reason>Solution-shaped opportunities collapse the distinction between need and proposed answer, preventing the team from validating the underlying problem.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Discovery-delivery balance (15–20% capacity) is fictional in most teams — engineers stay at 100% delivery, PM does discovery alone, trio collapses to PM-only.</description>
        <reason>Discovery-delivery percentage is a contract with engineering, not a PM aspiration. If 15% gets eaten weekly, escalate or shrink scope; do not silently absorb it.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Outcome metric ambiguity — many PMs pick activation/retention proxies that the team can't actually move in a quarter. Agent-driven OST inherits the bad outcome and produces noise.</description>
        <reason>Pin the outcome_id. New wording = new outcome = new tree. Outcome metrics must be directly movable by the team in a quarter, not proxy metrics that conflate causation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Past-behavior interviews still surface aspirational answers when the prompt is loose; LLM transcript-coding amplifies this, mistaking interviewer leading questions for customer signal.</description>
        <reason>Interview-prep must produce questions about specific recent instances ("tell me about the last time you..."), never future predictions. Coder must label every quote as past_behavior | preference | speculation; synthesizer must filter to past_behavior only.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Synthesis collapses when interview corpora cross > 100 transcripts without theming — naive embedding-based clustering returns shallow themes ("users want speed"). Hierarchical theming (axial coding) is needed.</description>
        <reason>Require N>=5 quotes from >=3 participants before emitting a theme. Do not manufacture cross-cutting themes from N=2 unrelated quotes.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Tree visualization tools (Miro/FigJam) become the bottleneck — a YAML/JSON tree-as-code is more agent-friendly but humans don't love it.</description>
        <reason>Pin OST as YAML; use mermaid-cli or graphviz to render SVG for stakeholder meetings. Agents are fast on code; don't force them to manipulate design tools.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Memory creep across weeks: agents fed last-week's "decisions" treat them as immutable, blocking re-litigation. Always include a revisited_ok: true flag in the prompt for opportunities older than 30 days.</description>
        <reason>Opportunities should be revisitable; otherwise the team locks in bad assumptions. Explicit revisit flags let teams re-negotiate old decisions when new evidence arrives.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Calendar contention: agents auto-book interviews into PM's deep-work blocks; require a "discovery zone" calendar block as the only legal slot.</description>
        <reason>Interview scheduling must respect PM's focus time. A "discovery zone" block signals availability and prevents agent-driven interview scheduling from disrupting the week.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Customer recordings often contain SSN, contract terms, internal company info. Run a PII scrubber pre-coding; never feed raw recordings to a remote LLM without redaction.</description>
        <reason>PII scrubbing is a mandatory gating step before agent ingestion. Compliance and privacy require local redaction before any remote processing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="weekly-cron">
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
0 8  * * 1   claude run /discovery-feedback-triage
0 9  * * 2   claude run /discovery-interview-prep
0 16 * * 2   claude run /discovery-interview-code   # after interview
0 9  * * 3   claude run /discovery-ost-synthesize
0 9  * * 4   claude run /discovery-trio-prep
0 16 * * 5   claude run /discovery-weekly-readout
0 9  1 */3 * claude run /discovery-roadmap-mapper   # quarterly
]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apis">
      <p>Integration points for feedback sources and collaboration tools:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>All agent integration happens through files in `.aidocs/product_docs/discovery/`. No in-app SaaS state without an export step. This keeps the OST portable and queryable.</statement>
        <rationale>File-based state lets agents version-control the tree, run diffs, and keep everything queryable via simple grep/yaml parsing. SaaS-only state becomes a black box the moment the tool changes pricing or API.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Feedback ingest sources (support tickets, NPS, sales calls, app-store reviews) MUST be mapped to the OST via standardized fields: source, date, user_id, segment, verbatim. Never ingest raw data without annotation.</statement>
        <rationale>Annotated ingest lets agents weight by segment and avoid false-positive clustering from identical generic complaints across different sources.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

